{
  "text": "To reduce the limitation of measurement conditions, in the past few decades various NAH methods have been developed, such as the boundary element method (BEM) [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] , the statistically optimized near-field acoustic holography (SONAH) [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] , and the equivalent source method (ESM) [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . ESM, also known as wave superposition method (WSM), is an efficacious method for identifying sound sources. For ESM, it assumes that the sound field is a superposition of some equivalent sound sources and approximates the boundary conditions by placing several simple sound sources. The calculation error and robustness analysis results of ESM show that it is an effective method with high precision [CITATION_7] .",
